## Key decisions explained

### Per-step `try/catch` blocks (not one big `try`)
Each operation gets its own `try/catch` so errors are re-thrown with the **exact same prefix string** as the original (`"Failed to read input:"`, `"Failed to parse data:"`, etc.). A single outer `try/catch` would lose that per-step context.

### `validateRecords` return shape
The original callback delivered **two separate values** — `(null, validRecords, invalidCount)`. Since an async function can only `return` one value, they're bundled into an object `{ validRecords, invalidCount }` and destructured at the call site:
```javascript
({ validRecords, invalidCount } = await validateRecords(parsedRecords));
```

### `setTimeout` → `await new Promise(...)`
The `setTimeout(..., 10)` calls that simulate async I/O are preserved as:
```javascript
await new Promise(resolve => setTimeout(resolve, 10));
```
placed **after** the synchronous work in each helper — matching the original pattern where processing runs first and the result is delivered asynchronously.

### Error timing in helpers
In the original, even thrown errors were delivered via `setTimeout` (asynchronously). In the async/await version, a throw before the `await` rejects the returned Promise immediately (no 10ms delay). This is the one unavoidable micro-timing difference, but it is behaviorally invisible to any `await`-ing caller.

